{{Infobox mine | name = Belle Ayr | image = | width = | caption = | pushpin_map = Wyoming | pushpin_label = Belle Ayr Mine | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Wyoming | coordinates = {{coord|44|06|09|N|105|25|07|W|region:US|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | place = | subdivision_type = [[U.S. state|State]] | state/province = [[Wyoming]] | country = [[United States]] | owner = [[Alpha Natural Resources]] | official website = http://www.alphanr.com | acquisition year = 2009 | stock_exchange = NYSE | stock_code = ANR | products = [[Coal]] | financial year = | amount = | opening year = 1972 | closing year = }}
==Overview==
The '''Belle Ayr''' mine is a [[coal mine]] located 18 miles southeast of [[Gillette, Wyoming|Gillette]], [[Wyoming]] in the United States in the coal-rich [[Powder River Basin]]. The mine is an [[open-pit mining|open pit]], "truck and shovel", mine producing a low-sulfur, sub-bituminous coal from the Wyodak-Anderson seam that is used for domestic energy generation. Coal produced by the mine is shipped to its customers via [[railroad]]. The mine is currently owned and operated by [[Blackjewel LLC]] after being acquired in a merger with [[Contura energy]] in 2017.<ref name="ANR">{{cite web|url=http://www.alphanr.com/poweringthefuture/locations/Pages/default.aspx|title=Alpha Natural Resources: Locations|work=Alpha Natural Resources website|publisher=Alpha Natural Resources|accessdate=2010-06-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100719024849/http://www.alphanr.com/poweringthefuture/locations/Pages/default.aspx| archivedate= 19 July 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
As of 2009, Belle Ayr had reserves of 406&nbsp;mm tons of sub-bituminous coal and a maximum permitted production capacity of 45mm tons per year. Typical annual production has been in 26-28mm ton range for the last several years though. The average quality of the coal shipped from Belle Ayr is 8,550 BTU/lb, 0.33% Sulfur, 4.50% Ash, and 1.90% Sodium (of the ash). Train loading operations at the mine are done with a batch weigh bin system that is coupled to a "weigh-in-motion" track scale system. Silo capacity at the mine's rail loop, which can accommodate up to 5 [[unit trains]], is 46,000 tons.<ref name="BNSF">{{cite web|url=http://www.bnsf.com/customers/pdf/mineguide.pdf#page=6|title=Mine Guide|work=BNSF website|publisher=BNSF|accessdate=2010-06-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121025048/http://bnsf.com/customers/pdf/mineguide.pdf#page=6|archive-date=2010-11-21|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> In 2008, the mine produced just over 28.7 million [[short ton]]s of coal, making it the 7th-most productive coal mine in the United States.<ref name="EIA">{{cite web|url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/coal/page/acr/table9.html|title=Major U.S. Coal Mines, 2008|date=September 2009|publisher=[[Energy Information Administration]] of the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]]|accessdate=2010-06-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100611163617/http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/coal/page/acr/table9.html| archivedate= 11 June 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
==History==
The Belle Ayr Mine began operations in 1972 and is the oldest, non-captive mine in the [[Powder River Basin]]. Since mining operations began, the mine has shipped over 574 million tons of coal to its customers.<ref name="UP">{{cite web|url=http://www.uprr.com/customers/energy/coal/sprb/belleayr.shtml|title=UP: Belle Ayr Mine|work=Union Pacific website|publisher=Union Pacific|accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref> The Belle Ayr mine has changed hands many times through mergers and sales. Previous owners include AMAX, Cyprus AMAX, RAG, and Foundation Coal.
In 2007, Belle Ayr was awarded a Director's Award from the [[Office of Surface Mining]] for its [[stream restoration|restoration]] work on [[Caballo Creek]], which winds its way through the Belle Ayr Mine property.<ref name="BW">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Belle+Ayr+Mine+Receives+Reclamation+Award.-a0168820056|title=Belle Ayr Mine Receives Reclamation Award|date=September 19, 2007|work=Business Wire|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=2009-04-22}}</ref>
==Production== <ref name="WMA">{{cite web|url=http://www.wma-minelife.com/coal/prbc/belleayr.htm|title=Belle Ayr Data|date=June 13, 2010|publisher=Wyoming Mining Association|accessdate=2010-06-14|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718075412/http://www.wma-minelife.com/coal/prbc/belleayr.htm|archivedate=July 18, 2011|df=}}</ref><ref name="Kost">{{cite web|url=http://library.corporate-ir.net/library/18/182/182719/items/247865/Kost.pdf#page=6| title=Powder River Basin Operations and Process Management|date=May 30, 2007|publisher=Foundation Coal West|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref><ref name="MSHA">{{cite web|url=http://www.msha.gov/drs/drshome.htm| title=MSHA Mine ID 4800732|accessdate=2010-07-03| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100624093018/http://www.msha.gov/drs/drshome.htm| archivedate= 24 June 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
