{{Infobox NRHP | name =Colter's Hell | nrhp_type = | image = Colters_Hell.jpg | caption = | location = [[Park County, Wyoming|Park County]], [[Wyoming|Wyoming, USA]] | nearest_city= [[Cody, Wyoming]] | coordinates = {{coord|44|30|53|N|109|7|2|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Wyoming#USA | area = | built = | architect= | architecture= | added = August 14, 1973<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref> | governing_body = Bureau of Reclamation | refnum=73001937 }}
'''Colter's Hell''' is an area of [[fumarole]]s and hot springs on the [[Shoshone River]] near [[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Wyoming]]. The thermal area covers about a square mile at the mouth of the Shoshone's canyon. Its thermal activity has declined ever since its description by [[mountain man]] [[John Colter]], who parted from the [[Lewis & Clark Expedition]] prior to its conclusion and passed through the region in the winter of 1807-1808. Colter's account of the features on what was then called the Stinkingwater River has subsequently been confused with the much more extensive and powerful geysers in [[Yellowstone National Park]], which Colter may not have actually visited.<ref name="nrhpinv1">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=73001937}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory - Nomination Form: Colter's Hell|last=Frost|first=Ned|date=December 19, 1969|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2009-07-29}}</ref>
Other early descriptions of Colter's Hell date back to the trapper [[Joseph Meek]] in the year of 1830 as well as to [[Plenty Coups]], a chief of the [[Absarokee]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Indians]], who camped with his tribe at the thermal area in 1840. Meek had seen geyser basin in Yellowstone and described Colter's Hell in similar terms, implying that there were active geysers at his visit. Today the area consists of hot springs and steam vents.<ref name="nrhpinv1"/> Several extinct geyser or hot spring cones stand up to {{convert|30|ft|m}} high on the riverbank. Other hot springs were located near the confluence of the north and south forks of the Shoshone, now drowned under the reservoir created by [[Buffalo Bill Dam]].<ref name="chjh1">{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/grte1/chap4.htm |title=Chapter IV: "Colter's Hell": A Case of Mistaken Identity |last=Mattes |first=Merrill J. |year=1962 |work=Colter's Hell and Jackson's Hole |publisher=Yellowstone Association & Grand Teton Natural History Association |accessdate=2009-07-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231133006/http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/grte1/chap4.htm |archivedate=2009-12-31 |df= }}</ref>
The notion that Colter's Hell referred to one of the geyser basins of Yellowstone first appeared in [[Hiram M. Chittenden]]'s 1895 book ''Yellowstone National Park.'' However, Chittenden went on to describe a "tar spring" on the Stinkingwater as well under the same name. Chittenden's speculation contradicts the earliest published description of the site in [[Washington Irving]]'s account of Captain [[Benjamin Bonneville|Benjamin L.E. Bonneville]]'s journals of Bonneville's scouts' visit to the location in 1833, the same year that another of Bonneville's survey parties discovered the geyser basins of Yellowstone along the [[Firehole River]].<ref name="chjh1"/>
Colter's Hell is just to the north of [[US 14]]-[[US 16|16]]-[[US 20|20]] on the west side of Cody. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1973.<ref name="nris"/>
