{{italic title}} [[File:Knot1.png|thumb|right|An illustration of a knot garden layout from the book]] The '''''Complete English Gardener''''' is a practical guide to [[gardening]] first published in 1670 by English author Leonard Meager. The original title is '''''The English Gardener, or, A Sure Guide to Young Planters and Gardeners: in Three Parts'''''.
''The Complete English Gardener'' was among many gardening books released after [[John Parkinson (botanist)|John Parkinson]]'s ''Paradisi in Sole'' in 1629.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bushnell|first1=Rebecca W.|title=Green Desire: Imagining Early Modern English Gardens|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0801441439|page=74|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4FAyxoRJVJEC&pg=PA74|language=en}}</ref> It was very popular and went through many editions,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fussell|first1=G. E.|title=The Old English Farming Books From Fitzherbert To Tull 1523 To 1730|publisher=Read Books Ltd|isbn=9781473383715|page=72|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MO99CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT72|accessdate=18 September 2016|language=en}}</ref> and was republished as ''The Compleat English Gardener'' in 1704 with a supplement, ''The New Art of Gardening; with the Gardener's Almanack''.<ref>{{cite wikisource|title=Meager, Leonard (DNB00)|last=Hewins|first=William Albert Samuel|year=|wslink =Dictionary of National Biography|page=|wspage=|scan=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wyman|first=Donald|title=Wyman's Gardening encyclopedia|date=1988|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-02-632070-2|page=523}}</ref>
It contains a variety of gardening advice, including how to grow [[grape]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Castle|first=Steven|date=5 November 1887|title=Jottings on old garden literature|journal=The Horticultural Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nt5IAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA300|page=300}}</ref> The book's influence extended to the American [[Province of Massachusetts Bay|colony of Massachusetts]]. The book was described by author Ann Leighton as "the epitome of all the handy books on gardening which were becoming plentiful in a time when books of instruction from those purporting to be experts were greatly in vogue."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leighton|first1=Ann|title=Early American Gardens: For Meate Or Medicine|publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|isbn=0870235303|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WtqsKBE2VVQC&pg=PA174|accessdate=18 September 2016|language=en|year= 1970}}</ref>
